<entry>
    <title>Renaissance painting shows how watermelons looked before selective breeding</title>
    <link rel="alternate" type="text/html" href="http://kottke.org/15/07/renaissance-painting-shows-how-watermelons-looked-before-selective-breeding" />
    <id>tag:kottke.org,2015://5.26655</id>

    <published>2015-07-29T17:07:33Z</published>
    <updated>2015-07-29T17:07:33Z</updated>

    <author>
        <name>Jason Kottke</name>
        <uri>http://www.kottke.org</uri>
    </author>
    <content type="html" xml:lang="en" xml:base="http://kottke.org/">
        <![CDATA[<p>A <a href="http://www.christies.com/lotfinder/paintings/giovanni-stanchi-watermelons-peaches-pears-a-5765893-details.aspx">painting of fruit</a> done by Giovanni Stanchi sometime in the mid 1600s shows that the watermelon has <a href="http://www.vox.com/2015/7/28/9050469/watermelon-breeding-paintings">changed somewhat</a> in the intervening 350 years.</p>

<p><img src="http://also.kottke.org/misc/images/renaissance-watermelon.jpg" width="640" height="469" border="0" alt="Renaissance watermelon" /></p>

<blockquote><p>That's because over time, we've bred watermelons to have the bright red color we recognize today. That fleshy interior is actually the watermelon's placenta, which holds the seeds. Before it was fully domesticated, that placenta lacked the high amounts of lycopene that give it the red color. Through hundreds of years of domestication, we've modified smaller watermelons with a white interior into the larger, lycopene-loaded versions we know today.</p></blockquote>

<p>(via <a href="https://twitter.com/robinsloan">@robinsloan</a>)</p>]]>



