        <name>Jason Kottke</name>
        <uri>http://www.kottke.org</uri>
    </author>
    <content type="html" xml:lang="en" xml:base="http://kottke.org/">
        <![CDATA[<p>Using images found on the internet through Google's visually similar images feature, NASA, U.S. Geological Survey, and various mapping services, Kelli Anderson <a href="http://www.kellianderson.com/remixed/">recreated</a> part of the Eames' iconic <a href="http://kottke.org/10/10/powers-of-ten">Powers of Ten</a> as a flipbook. Watch a video here:</p>

<p><iframe src="https://player.vimeo.com/video/134406960?title=0&byline=0&portrait=0" width="640" height="461" frameborder="0" webkitallowfullscreen mozallowfullscreen allowfullscreen></iframe></p>

<p>Or <a href="http://www.kellianderson.com/remixed/">play around with a virtual flipbook</a> at Anderson's site. This could not possibly be anymore in my wheelhouse. <a href="http://kellianderson.com/blog/2015/07/the-internet-is-really-big/">Here's the nitty gritty</a> on how she made it happen.</p>

<blockquote><p>The inspiration for making discontinuous-bits-of-culture into something continuous goes back to 2011. Some of my friends camped out on a sidewalk to see Christian Marclay's The Clock. Like a loser with a deadline, I missed out-only catching it years later at MoMA. In the day-long film, Marclay recreates each minute of the 24-our day using clips from films featuring the current time-on a clock or watch. It runs in perfect synchronization with the audience's day (so: while a museum crowd slumps sleepily in their chairs at 6am, starlets hit snooze on the clocks onscreen.)</p></blockquote>]]>



