    <content type="html" xml:lang="en" xml:base="http://kottke.org/">
        <![CDATA[<p><img src="http://also.kottke.org/misc/images/f21-thread-screen.jpg" width="640" height="679" border="0" alt="F21 Thread Screen" /></p>

<p>Clothing retailer Forever 21 hired product and prototyping company <a href="http://breakfastny.com/">Breakfast</a> to build them <a href="http://f21threadscreen.com/">a giant screen made out of spools of thread to "print" people's Instagram photos</a>. <a href="http://breakfastny.com/thread-screen">The screen</a>, which Breakfast bills as "one of the most complex machines ever built for a brand", weighs 2000 pounds, measures 11 ft high, 9 ft wide, and 3 ft deep, and has a resolution of 80x80 spool pixels. Here's how they made it:</p>

<p><iframe width="640" height="360" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/dvDHNDkO-Qo?rel=0" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></p>

<p>If you want to give it a try, just tag an Instagram photo with #F21ThreadScreen and it'll print it out for you (<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Staau2OCVuY">watch the live stream</a>). Prior art alert: the first time I remember seeing something like this was <a href="http://www.smoothware.com/danny/woodenmirror.html">Daniel Rozin's Wooden Mirror (1999)</a> at ITP (<a href="https://vimeo.com/7820888">video here</a>).</p>]]>



